				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: guild help<a name="54240"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 29 04 10:08 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>If theres any one thing you take away from guilds, its that people need motivation to stick around. Most people joining guilds at lvl 50-60 have no intention of staying guilded once they hit 65 and have enough AAs/flags behind them to start playing with the bigger guilds. This is the challenge most smaller guilds face, how to keep people in the guild after having spent so much time upgrading them, getting epics, and minor flags which ultimately gives them room to upgrade their status.
<br />

<br />
Its a little pessimistic, sure, but its what I observe to happen.
<br />

<br />
Things you can do(not sure how your guild leadership structure works) would be events that build relationships among members. Raid old content like Kael or ToV(Velious content is still some of the most memorable). Get keys for Sleepers. Try to coordinate guild exp groups rather than have all the member's go find pickups. With a guild trying to break into routine raiding its important not to over-do it as well. Figure out the work-schedule of people in guild and set specific days of the week for raids when most people can be on. Build inter-guild relationships early.
<br />

<br />
Ehh sorry started rambling off-topic...just my thoughts on breaking a guild into raiding.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
