				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: guild help<a name="54277"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 29 04 12:00 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">If theres any one thing you take away from guilds, its that people need motivation to stick around. Most people joining guilds at lvl 50-60 have no intention of staying guilded once they hit 65 and have enough AAs/flags behind them to start playing with the bigger guilds.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Second this.  I was an officer for about two years in a guild that basically turned into a feeder guild - every time we'd get to a certain point in guild progression and finally beat something that we'd been working on for a long time, we'd have a dozen or so people leave the next week.  Never quite understood how that worked, but it got to be a pretty observable pattern. <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
I'd actually skip the Kael arena, HOT, and Sleeper's parts of the raiding game these days - encourage people to LDoN together and gear up from the bazaar, and then do NToV/Luclin/PoP targets.   Kill Kael named, sure, Vindi and such, but don't grind the arena or HoT.  People will look at the stats on velious quest armor and ask &quot;why bother?&quot;
<br />

<br />
Give folks value for the time they put in, and they'll be happy and stick around.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
