			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: guild help<a name="54639"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 1 04 4:21 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Well, I come from a guild that went from first emperor kill to time flagged in nine months.  On a server with restricted access to boss mobs because of a calendar booking arrangement.  You don't have to stay a feeder guild if you dont want to.
<br />

<br />
I think more important than gear is training your folks to raid hard.  If you have a core of people who would like to raid several times a week, you can climb rather impressively.
<br />

<br />
First, train your people to organize themselves on a raid.  Never have the raid leader make groups, set up heal rotations, and generally micromanage raids.   Raid leader invites healers as group leaders and says form groups.  Your guildies can generally organize themselves more or less in the right way.  Let the clerics/healers organize their own rots, etc.
<br />

<br />
Second, train your people to manage their agro.  Raid leader needs to say things like &quot;Less dying, ppl!&quot;  One of the hardest things for me to learn joining a hardcore raiding guild is sometimes NOT to sing.  Just shut up and be a lump.
<br />

<br />
Third, train your people to deal with chaos.  Puller needs to show up with 4 or 6 red con mobs once in a while.  Tanks need to learn to stay sharp and jump on mobs to split tank unmezzables, etc.  Healers need to heal their tanks, organize without being told everything.
<br />

<br />
Fourth, keep stretching what you can do, pushing the envellope.  Never farm easy targets over and over.  Nothing will make you a feeder guild faster than doing the same content over and over, cause Joe who just joined needs better gear.  Joe can come along with you to the hard stuff without gear and learn while dying.  If you are teetering along, just barely winning encounters, and always moving to harder targets, no one is gonna wanna leave.  Its just too exciting being part of a guild that is going someplace.  You ought to be failing about 20% of the raids you are doing or you are stalled.  More than 20% or so, and people will get discouraged.  Less than that they will get bored.
<br />

<br />
Gear is important, yes.  But not as important as how your folks fight, and what they feel about their guild.  Encourage your people to level as much as they can.  But also set times for raids and make it understood that if you are on during raid time, you are sorta expected to make raids a priority.
<br />

<br />
Some random thoughts here put together rather quickly.  You may not agree with some of the things i am saying.  That's cool.  But please be nice when you criticize me, ok?  Hehe!</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
